<font color="#FF0000">YOUR COMMENTS/WHAT'S NEXT</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr  7 15:23:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Many people have posted messages -- on this board and by private e-mail -- telling us how important these dialogues are to them and urging us to find a way to keep the &quot;interactivity&quot; of this site going. <br><br>
Thank you, to all of you who have written about your concerns, but especially to all of you who've been willing to engage in these amazing multi-threaded dialogues over the past weeks and months.  Your spirit, your honesty, your respectfulness have really made this a site unlike any other.   I -- and many others -- have learned so much here.<br><br>
Please understand that we're doing everything we possibly can to keep the site &quot;alive and interactive.&quot;  It is everything we hoped and dreamed it would become -- a real gathering place for people with different perspectives and experiences to begin to listen to (and learn from) each other.  <br><br>
There are a few possible ways in which the site can continue, and I'll talk about that a little later in this message.  Right now I need to provide a little context.<br><br>
It may not be apparent, but a fair amount of work goes into launching a site like this and keeping it operating smoothly.  Most people who do the level of work that's required expect (and deserve) to be paid for their services.  P.O.V. Interactive is a small struggling non-profit that does not have a magic purse.  We raised some money in 1996 to develop and launch the site, and all of that went to pay the designers.  We've been paying other consultants and our staff out of our own budget since September, while we've tried to raise more money.  At this point, we've subsidized the site with well over $30,000. <br><br>
By putting that notice up in March, we were trying to &quot;do the right thing.&quot; Some feel that it's taken all the life out of the dialogues here and if that's true, we feel terrible about it.  But even so, we couldn't have done it differently, for two reasons: 1) we hoped against hope that someone who values the site would read the notice and be able to help; and 2) we knew that we couldn't afford to keep it going forever and, out of respect for the people who've put so much of themselves into it, we didn't want to &quot;pull the plug&quot; without warning.<br><br>
So what next?  Several things.  <br><br>
First, the site will stay active at least until Memorial Day.  One of our staff members has volunteered to do the &quot;maintenance&quot; work on her own time until then.<br><br>
Second, we've had a few nibbles from people who said they might be interested in contributing to keep the site going here.  Nothing has materialized so far, so we're not sure how likely that is to happen.  By the way, it seems to us that the most logical thing would be to find someone who cares about what's happening here high enough in a large corporation that they could set it up for their company to &quot;underwrite&quot; the site and take credit for it.  Anybody know Fred Smith at FedEx (he's a Vietnam Vet and the president of FedEx.)<br><br>
Third, we've been talking with people who run another Website about taking over the dialogue.  We can't say who they are right now, but it'd be exactly the right place for these discussions to continue.<br><br>
Fourth, in the next week or two we'll be introducing the next wave of dialogue.  Back in late February we invited about a dozen people who'd posted in this area to join a &quot;private,&quot; moderated discussion on an electronic mailing list.  The idea was to see if folks could go even deeper into some of the issues being explored in these pages.  We would then put excerpts of the discussion on the dialog page and invite further postings.  <br><br>
We were surprised (but not unhappy) that that discussion really took off, generating something like 350 pages of printouts.  But that volume of material made it necessary for us to bring on someone who could bring it down to a manageable size.  It's a three week full time job!<br><br>
We're finally nearing the end of that process and hope to have the stuff up soon. The dialogue area will remain interactive for several weeks after that goes up so there can be an opportunity for comments, responses, etc.<br><br>
Finally, several people have written to us saying what's here already is an amazing archive.  We agree, and we've actually had one inquiry from someone who's interested in trying to build a book from the material here.  We're going to follow up on that, but if you know anyone else who might be interested, please have them get in touch with us.  <br><br>
Let me close this very long message by saying, in the spirit of these pages, that we continue to welcome any comments, questions, etc.  Sometimes it's a little overwhelming here and we can't always respond to each message individually.  But please be assured that we read -- and value -- everything.<br><br>
Marc Weiss<br>
President,<br>
P.O.V. Interactive
